/**************************************************** JAVA *******************************************/

Better Approach - using HashMap to store numbers and their index, then findthe  target to get the value from the map and their index
class Solution {
    public int[] twoSum(int[] nums, int target) {
        int n = nums.length; // Get the length of the array
        Map<Integer, Integer> mp = new HashMap<>(); // Create a HashMap to store numbers and their indices
        // Iterate through the array
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int remaining = target - nums[i]; // Calculate the required complement
            // If the complement exists in the map, return the indices
            if (mp.containsKey(remaining)) {
                return new int[]{mp.get(remaining), i}; // Return the stored index and current index
            }
            // Store the current number and its index in the map
            mp.put(nums[i], i);
        }
        // Return an empty array if no solution is found (this case won't occur based on problem constraints)
        return new int[]{};
    }
}
Time Complexity :- O(N).
Space Complexity :- O(N).

Brute Force Approach - using two loops outer loop for picking the first elements, and an inner loop for check pair with the first element.

class Solution {
    public int[] twoSum(int[] nums, int target) {
        // Outer loop: pick the first element
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            // Inner loop: check pairs with the element at index i
            for (int j = i + 1; j < nums.length; j++) {
                // If the sum of the two elements equals the target
                if (nums[i] + nums[j] == target) {
                    // Return the indices of the two numbers
                    return new int[]{i, j};
                }
            }
        }
        // If no valid pair is found (as per problem constraints, this usually won't happen)
        return new int[]{};
    }
}
Time Complexity :- O(N^2).
Space Complexity :- O(1).
